metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
We have put some limits on the service to make sure we provide you a good default to start with, while also keeping it a good experience for all other users using Inngest.
Some of these limits are customizable, so if you need more than what the current limits provide, please
[contact us](\contact)
and we can update the limits for you.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
The following applies to
```
step
```
usage.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Sleep duration
Sleep (with
```
step.sleep()
```
and
```
step.sleepUntil()
```
) up to a year, and for free plan up to seven days. Check the
[pricing page](\pricing)
for more information.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Timeout
Each step has a timeout depending on the hosting provider of your choice (
[see more info](\docs\usage-limits\providers)
), but Inngest supports up to
```
2 hours
```
at the maximum.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Concurrency Upgradable
Check your concurrency limits on the
[billing page](https://app.inngest.com/billing)
. See the
[pricing page](https://www.inngest.com/pricing)
for more info about the concurrency limits in all plans.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Payload Size
The limit for data returned by a step is
```
4MB
```
.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Function run state size
Function run state cannot exceed
```
32MB
```
. Its state includes:
- Event data (multiple events if using batching)
- Step-returned data
- Function-returned data
- Internal metadata ( *small - around a few bytes* )

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Functions
Number of Steps per Function
The maximum number of steps allowed per function is
```
1000
```
.
⚠️
This limit is easily reached if you're using
```
step
```
on each item in a loop.
Instead we recommend one or both of the following:
- Process the loop within a `step` and return that data
- Utilize the [fan out](\docs\guides\fan-out-jobs) feature to process each item in a separate function

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Events
Name length
The maximum length allowed for an event name is
```
256
```
characters.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Events
Request Body Size Upgradable
The maximum event payload size is dependent on your billing plan. The default on the Free Tier is
```
256KB
```
and is upgradable to
```
3MB
```
. See
[the pricing page](\pricing?ref=docs-usage-limits)
for additional detail.

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Events
Number of events per request Customizable
Maximum number of events you can send in one request is
```
5000
```
.
If you're doing fan out, you'll need to be aware of this limitation when you run
```
step.sendEvent(events)
```
.
TypeScript Go Python
Copy Copied
```
// this `events` list will need to be <= 5000
const events = [{name : "<event-name>" , data : {}} , ... ];

await step .sendEvent ( "send-example-events" , events);
// or
await inngest .send (events);
```

metadata.title: #### On this page
metadata.content:
Usage Limits
Events
Batch size
The hard limit of a batch size is 10 MiB regardless of the
```
timeout
```
or
```
maxSize
```
limit.
Meaning the batch will be started if that limit is crossed even if the batch is not full or has not reached the timeout duration configured.
